Citations
Date: 0/0/1949
Source: Personal Communication
Author: MASON
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: Paki [pa:ki:] Heard in Christchurch for a bald spot on the head from a man who was often on the West coast in the course of his work.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1966
Source: English Language in Aust. & NZ, The
Author: TURNER
Vol / Page: 161
Edition:
Quote: An indigenous one is <i>pakihi</i>, a natural clearing in the bush ... on the West Coast. It has been facetiously applied to a man's bald patch, but the word in its basic meaning is not very common and this transferred sense even less so.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1988
Source: Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author: MCGILL
Vol / Page: 82
Edition:
Quote: paki/pakihi bald patch on a man's head, from Maori word 'pakihi' for a natural clearing in the bush.
